rows.title: Top Volume Backend WAFL Layer Drilldown

panels.description: Average latency contribution from the network service center.  Includes latency from outside the cluster such as waiting on SCSI XFER_RDY in SAN configurations.  If latency is high, check for saturation on your network or host accessing the volume.
panels.title: Latency from Network

panels.description: Average latency contribution from the QoS throttle service center.  Includes latency added on purpose to keep the workload within the limit of its policy group. If latency is high, consider increasing the policy group limit.
panels.title: Latency from Throttle

panels.description: Average latency contribution from the node that owns the LIF of an incoming request to translate from the protocol to a ONTAP specific request.  If latency is high, check CPU utilization on the node owning the LIF being used to access the volume.
panels.title: Latency from Frontend

panels.description: Average latency contribution to service indirect traffic for the volume. Includes latency between the node owning the LIF and the node owning the volume.  If latency is high, verify the health of the cluster network, and consider co-locating the LIF and data volume on the same node.
panels.title: Latency from Cluster

panels.description: Average latency contribution for ONTAP WAFL to process an IO on the node that owns the volume.  If latency is high, check CPU utilization on the node owning the volume.
panels.title: Latency from Backend

panels.description: Average latency contribution waiting on disk access needed to service a request.  If latency is high, check disk busy of the aggregate hosting the volume and if it is high consider moving to an aggregate capable of servicing more IOPs [such as SSD]
panels.title: Latency from Disk

panels.description: Average latency contribution from ONTAP WAFL suspends due to prerequisite data not being available to service a request.
panels.title: Latency from Suspend

panels.description: Average latency contribution waiting on cloud object storage (FabricPool feature) needed to service a request.  If latency is high, consider not using the FabricPool feature for this volume.
panels.title: Latency from Cloud

panels.description: Average latency contribution from NVLOG mirroring of data to other node(s) in the cluster.  If latency is high, check for network saturation between the cluster nodes. For ONTAP Select and ONTAP Cloud configurations also check the CPU utilization of the other cluster nodes.
panels.title: Latency from NVLOG Mirroring

rows.title: Top Volume QoS Latency From Drilldown

panels.description: Average request count, per volume, in the chosen time window, to object storage.  Not scaled per second, but a cumulative count (delta) since the previous poll.
panels.title: Top Volumes with Object Storage Requests

panels.description: Average request count, per volume and type to object storage.  Not scaled per second, but a cumulative count (delta) since the previous poll.
panels.title: Top Volumes with Object Storage Requests

panels.description: Average latency per GET operation to object storage
panels.title: Object Storage GET Latency

panels.description: Total GET request count, per volume, in the collection interval to object storage.  Not scaled per second, but a cumulative count (delta) since the previous poll.
panels.title: Object Storage GET Request Count

panels.description: Average latency per PUT operation to object storage
panels.title: Object Storage PUT Latency

panels.description: Total PUT request count, per volume, in the collection interval to object storage.  Not scaled per second, but a cumulative count (delta) since the previous poll.
panels.title: Object Storage PUT Request Count
